## 🚀 Modern JavaScript (ES6+)

ECMAScript 2015 (ES6) and subsequent versions transformed JavaScript from a simple scripting language into a powerful, expressive development tool. These features are used every day in React, Node.js, and TypeScript.

---

## 1️⃣ Arrow Functions

```javascript
// Traditional function
function add(a, b) { return a + b }

// Arrow function (shorter)
const add = (a, b) => a + b  // Implicit return when no braces

// With body
const process = (data) => {
  const result = transform(data)
  return result
}

// No parentheses for single param
const double = x => x * 2
```

Key difference: Arrow functions do NOT have their own `this`, `arguments`, or `super`. They inherit `this` from the enclosing scope.

---

## 2️⃣ Destructuring

```javascript
// Array destructuring
const [a, b, ...rest] = [1, 2, 3, 4]
// a=1, b=2, rest=[3,4]

// Object destructuring
const { name, age, role = 'user' } = person  // with default value

// Rename while destructuring
const { name: personName } = person

// Nested destructuring
const { address: { city, zip } } = user

// Function parameter destructuring
function render({ title, children, className = '' }) {
  return `<div class="${className}"><h1>${title}</h1>${children}</div>`
}
```

---

## 3️⃣ Template Literals

```javascript
const name = "Mwero"
const score = 95

// Multi-line strings
const html = `
  <div>
    <h1>Hello, ${name}!</h1>
    <p>Score: ${score}</p>
    <p>Grade: ${score >= 90 ? 'A' : 'B'}</p>
  </div>
`

// Tagged template literals (advanced)
const sql = gql`
  query GetUser($id: ID!) {
    user(id: $id) { name email }
  }
`
```

---

## 4️⃣ Spread Operator (`...`)

```javascript
// Spread in arrays
const arr1 = [1, 2, 3]
const arr2 = [4, 5, 6]
const combined = [...arr1, ...arr2]  // [1,2,3,4,5,6]
const copy = [...arr1]               // Shallow copy

// Spread in objects
const user = { name: 'Mwero', age: 28 }
const updated = { ...user, age: 29 } // { name: 'Mwero', age: 29 }

// Spread in function calls
const numbers = [3, 1, 4, 1, 5]
Math.max(...numbers)  // Same as Math.max(3, 1, 4, 1, 5)
```

---

## 5️⃣ Rest Parameters

```javascript
// Collects remaining args into an array
function sum(...numbers) {
  return numbers.reduce((total, n) => total + n, 0)
}
sum(1, 2, 3, 4)  // 10

// In destructuring
const [first, ...others] = [1, 2, 3, 4]
// first=1, others=[2,3,4]
```

---

## 6️⃣ Enhanced Object Literals

```javascript
const name = "Mwero"
const age = 28

// Shorthand property names
const user = { name, age }  // { name: "Mwero", age: 28 }

// Shorthand methods
const obj = {
  greet() { return "Hello!" },  // Instead of greet: function() {...}
  get fullName() { return `${this.first} ${this.last}` } // Getter
}

// Computed property names
const key = "dynamicKey"
const data = { [key]: "value" }  // { dynamicKey: "value" }
```

---

## 7️⃣ Modules (ESModules)

```javascript
// math.js — exporting
export const PI = 3.14159
export function add(a, b) { return a + b }
export default class Calculator { ... }  // Default export

// app.js — importing
import Calculator from './math'           // Import default
import { PI, add } from './math'          // Import named
import * as math from './math'            // Import all as namespace
import { add as sum } from './math'       // Rename on import
```

---

## 8️⃣ Optional Chaining & Nullish Coalescing

```javascript
// Optional chaining (?.) — short-circuit if null/undefined
const city = user?.address?.city         // undefined (no error)
const price = cart?.items?.[0]?.price    // Works with arrays
const result = api?.getData?.()          // Works with methods

// Nullish coalescing (??) — default only for null/undefined
const name = user.name ?? "Anonymous"   // Only nulls get replaced
const count = data.count ?? 0           // 0 is not replaced!

// Compare with || which replaces all falsy values
const count2 = data.count || 0  // 0 would be replaced by 0 (same here)
// But: "" || "default" → "default" (empty string replaced!)
// And: "" ?? "default" → "" (empty string kept!)
```

---

## 9️⃣ `for...of` and Iterators

```javascript
// for...of (works on any iterable: arrays, strings, maps, sets)
for (const item of items) { ... }
for (const char of "Hello") { ... }
for (const [key, val] of map.entries()) { ... }

// for...in (for object keys — less common)
for (const key in object) {
  if (object.hasOwnProperty(key)) { ... }
}
```

---

## 🔟 Symbol, Map, and Set

```javascript
// Symbol — unique primitive value
const id = Symbol("id")
const id2 = Symbol("id")
id === id2  // false — always unique

// Map — ordered key-value store (keys can be any type)
const map = new Map()
map.set("key", "value")
map.get("key")   // "value"
map.has("key")   // true
map.size         // 1

// Set — unique values collection
const set = new Set([1, 2, 2, 3, 3])
// set = Set {1, 2, 3} — duplicates removed
set.add(4)
set.has(1)  // true
[...set]    // Convert to array
```

---

## 💡 Key Takeaways

| Feature | Purpose |
|---|---|
| Arrow functions | Concise, no own `this` |
| Destructuring | Extract values from arrays/objects cleanly |
| Template literals | Multi-line, embedded expressions |
| Spread `...` | Expand arrays/objects, shallow copy |
| Rest `...` | Collect remaining values |
| Optional chaining `?.` | Safe property access |
| Nullish coalescing `??` | Default only for null/undefined |
| ESModules | `import`/`export` for code organization |
| `Map` / `Set` | Better alternatives to plain objects/arrays in some cases |
